Thinking.text:
The mock's `removeEventListener` is buggy:
```js
removeEventListener(event) { delete this._listeners[event]; },
```

It doesn't take a function argument and just deletes the listener by event name. So calling `this.video.removeEventListener('play', this._onPlay)` does work to delete `_listeners.play`. But wait, my test failed. Let me trace through:

- After bind: `_listeners.play = this._onPlay`
- After unbind: `delete _listeners.play` → `_listeners.play` is undefined

But my test emits 3 events after unbind. Why did play trigger send?

Wait, let me re-read the unbind method:
```js
unbindVideoEvents() {
  if (this._onPlay) this.video.removeEventListener('play', this._onPlay);
  if (this._onPause) this.video.removeEventListener('pause', this._onPause);
  if (this._onSeeked) this.video.removeEventListener('seek', this._onSeeked);
  this._onPlay = null;
  this._onPause = null;
  this._onSeeked = null;
}
```

This looks correct. But the test does:
```js
send.clear();
video._emit('play');  // should not send
```

Wait, let me re-read the test setup:
```js
const video = createMockVideo({ currentTime: 10, duration: 100 });
const send = createMockSend();
const engine = makeEngine(video, send);

// 解绑前: 触发 play 应该 send
send.clear();
video._emit('play');
assert.strictEqual(send.calls.length, 1, '解绑前 play 事件应 send');

// 解绑
engine.unbindVideoEvents();
send.clear();

// 解绑后: 触发 play/pause/seeked 都不应 send
video._emit('play');
video._emit('pause');
video._emit('seeked');
assert.strictEqual(send.calls.length, 0, '解绑后 play/pause/seeked 都不应 send');
```

Hmm, "actual: 1" means after unbind and 3 emits, 1 call was made. So unbind is not actually removing the listener.

Let me check the mock again:
```js
addEventListener(event, fn) { this._listeners[event] = fn; },
removeEventListener(event) { delete this._listeners[event]; },
```

The mock's removeEventListener takes only one argument (event), but in my code I'm calling it with 2 args: `this.video.removeEventListener('play', this._onPlay)`. The mock ignores the 2nd arg, so it should still work. Let me check `_emit`:
```js
_emit(event) {
  const fn = v._listeners[event];
  if (fn) fn();
},
```

OK so after `delete _listeners.play`, `_emit('play')` should be a no-op. Unless... wait, the mock addEventListener assigns `this._listeners[event] = fn;` - that overwrites if called twice for same event. But in my bindVideoEvents, I call addEventListener 3 times for different events.

Oh wait! I see. Let me re-read my bindVideoEvents:
```js
this._onPlay = () => this.maybeSend('play');
this._onPause = () => this.maybeSend('pause');
this._onSeeked = () => this.maybeSend('seek');
this.video.addEventListener('play', this._onPlay);
this.video.addEventListener('pause', this._onPause);
this.video.addEventListener('seeked', this._onSeeked);
